PART 1 — VPC NETWORK FOUNDATION
Step 1: Create VPC
Login to AWS Console.
Search VPC in services.
Click Create VPC.
Select VPC only.
Enter:
Name: Custom-VPC
IPv4 CIDR: 10.0.0.0/16
Click Create VPC.
Wait for “Successfully created”.
Step 2: Create Public Subnet (Bastion)
Left menu → Subnets
Click Create subnet
Select Custom-VPC
Name: Public-Subnet
AZ: choose any (e.g., ap-south-1a)
CIDR: 10.0.1.0/24
Click Create.
Enable Auto Public IP:
Select Public-Subnet
Click Actions → Edit subnet settings
Enable Auto-assign public IPv4
Save
Step 3: Create Private Subnet (DB)
Create subnet again
Name: Private-Subnet
AZ: SAME as public subnet
CIDR: 10.0.2.0/24
Create

Do NOT enable public IP.

Step 4: Create Internet Gateway
Left menu → Internet Gateways
Click Create
Name: Custom-IGW
Create
Click Attach to VPC
Select Custom-VPC
Attach
Step 5: Create Public Route Table
Go to Route Tables
Click Create
Name: Public-RT
Select Custom-VPC
Create
Add Internet Route:
Select Public-RT
Go to Routes → Edit routes
Add:
Destination: 0.0.0.0/0
Target: Internet Gateway → select Custom-IGW
Save
Associate Public Subnet:
Go to Subnet Associations
Edit
Select Public-Subnet
Save
Step 6: Private Route Table
Create route table
Name: Private-RT
Select VPC
Create

Associate only Private-Subnet.
Do NOT add IGW route.

PART 2 — SECURITY GROUPS (CRITICAL)
Step 7: Bastion Security Group
Go to EC2 → Security Groups
Create security group
Name: Bastion-SG
VPC: Custom-VPC
Inbound:
Type: SSH
Port: 22
Source: My IP

Save.

Step 8: Database Security Group

Create new SG: DB-SG

Inbound Rules:
MySQL:
Port 3306
Source: 10.0.1.0/24
SSH:
Port 22
Source: Private IP of Bastion (later update)

No public access.

PART 3 — EC2 DEPLOYMENT
Step 9: Launch Bastion EC2
EC2 → Launch instance
Name: Bastion-Server
OS: Ubuntu
Instance type: t2.micro
Key pair: Create bastion.pem
Network:
VPC: Custom-VPC
Subnet: Public-Subnet
Auto-assign public IP: Enable
Security Group: Bastion-SG
Launch

Note down:

Public IP
Private IP
Step 10: Launch DB Server EC2
Launch instance
Name: DB-Server
OS: Ubuntu
Key pair: Create dbserver.pem
VPC: Custom-VPC
Subnet: Private-Subnet
Disable public IP
Security Group: DB-SG
Launch

Note private IP (10.0.2.x)

PART 4 — BASTION ACCESS FLOW
Step 11: SSH into Bastion (Local Machine)
ssh -i bastion.pem ubuntu@<BASTION_PUBLIC_IP>

If permission error:

chmod 400 bastion.pem
Step 12: Copy DB Key to Bastion

From your local system:

scp -i bastion.pem dbserver.pem ubuntu@<BASTION_PUBLIC_IP>:/home/ubuntu/

Now SSH again to Bastion.

Check:

ls

You should see dbserver.pem

Set permission:

chmod 400 dbserver.pem
Step 13: SSH to Private DB Server

Inside Bastion:

ssh -i dbserver.pem ubuntu@10.0.2.x

If connection fails:

Update DB-SG → Allow SSH from Bastion private IP

Connection successful = Bastion architecture working.

PART 5 — ADD NAT GATEWAY (Internet for Private)
Step 14: Create Elastic IP
EC2 → Elastic IPs
Allocate new
Save
Step 15: Create NAT Gateway
VPC → NAT Gateways
Create
Name: Custom-NAT
Subnet: Public-Subnet
Attach Elastic IP
Create

Wait until status = Available.

Step 16: Update Private Route Table
Go to Private-RT
Edit routes
Add:
Destination: 0.0.0.0/0
Target: NAT Gateway
Save
PART 6 — VERIFY INTERNET FROM PRIVATE

SSH:

Local → Bastion → DB server

Inside DB server:

sudo apt update

If it works = NAT working.

If not:

Check NAT in Public subnet
Check Private-RT association
Check IGW attached
